The National Curriculum in English is split into five attainment targets (ATs).
These are: speaking and listening, reading, writing, spelling and handwriting.

Of all these targets, reading is the one which most people regard as
fundamental.  If children cannot read they cannot write or spell, because they
have no knowledge of the written word or the letters making these words.

The more children practise their reading and the more fluent they become, the
easier all the other components of the National Curriculum in English will be.
When working on written English, children will be able to concentrate much
better on producing good written work if they can read and spell words fluently.

If they work with adults and discuss their work with them, they will develop
their speaking and listening skills, and then use these to improve their
vocabulary and written English.

The following table shows how Reading with ADI Junior relates to the National
Curriculum in English:

ATTAINMENT TARGET LEVELS        1       2       3
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
AT1 Speaking and Listening      X       x       x
AT2 Reading                     X       x       x
AT3 Writing                     X       x       x
AT4 Spelling                    X       x       x

X - aspects of the ATs which are covered by Reading with ADI Junior 6/7. 
x - aspects of the ATs which are only partially covered by Reading with
    ADI Junior 6/7.
	


JIGSAW WORDS: (click on apple on left)

Parts of the word appear under the pictures.  The child must make the word from
the parts at the bottom of the screen.  This develops reading and spelling
skills through observation.

Click on the part of the word and match it to the picture by placing it in the
boxes.

If you make a mistake click on it again and move it.  When all the words are
completed click on the Thumbs-Up icon and ADI Junior will check the words.



PICTURES IN ORDER: (click on apple on right)

Pictures appear and the child must create a logical story.  This uses
observation, logic and judgement to develop reading and comprehension skills.

   Level 1: Click on the next picture, at the bottom, which should continue the
            story started by the first picture.

   Level 2: You must decide which picture starts the story and then continue the
            story.  If you make a mistake click on the picture again to return 
            it to the bottom.

   Level 3: You must make a story that matches the picture by clicking on the
            appropriate phrase.  If you make a mistake click on the phrase on
            the page.

Click on the Thumbs-Up icon and ADI Junior will check the story.



TRUE OR FALSE: (click on the bird)

Decide whether the picture of phrase is true or false.  This develops
observation, logic and judgement.

Look at the picture, if one is shown, and read the phrase.  If it is true click
on the true robot.  If not click on the false robot.



SOUNDS AND PLACES: (click on bridge)

Different scenes are displayed and a question posed.  This develops listening
skills and also helps with reading and understanding.

   Levels 1 & 2: Click on the scene that the object or word shown at the bottom
                 would be most likely to make a sound.
                 
   Level 3: Click on the scene that answers the riddle.



LEARNING WORD SOUNDS: (click on blue chimney pipe)

Boxes appear with groups of letters in them.  This teaches children to recognise
common letter groups, and also develops reading and spelling skills.

Click on the box at the bottom that contains the letter or groups of letters
that can be heard in the word sound shown in the top box.



THE MATCHING GAME: (click on red chimney)

A memory game.  Children use observation, memory and judgement to develop
reading and spelling skills.

Click on a card and a picture or word will be displayed.  This must be matched
to another card.  They must all be matched up within the time limit shown by the
burning candle.



SYLLABLES AND WORDS (click on cloud)

Words have been cut up and the child must restore them.  This teaches children
to recognise common letter groups.

Click on the part of the word and match it to the picture by placing it in the
boxes.  If you make a mistake click on it again and move it.  When all the words
are completed, click on the thumbs-up icon and ADI Junior will check the words.



THE ODD ONE OUT (click on door of white house)

The child has to decide whether the phrase or picture does not belong.  This
uses observation, memory and judgement.  It will also develop reading with
understanding.

   Levels 1 & 2: Click on the picture that does not belong

   Level 3: Read the sentence and decide which phrase does not match.



FIND THE ANIMAL'S HOME (click on door of blue house)

A game of memory.  Children use observation, memory and judgement to develop
reading and spelling skills.

Click on a card and a picture or word will be displayed.  An animal must match
to its home or vice-versa.  They must all be matched by the time limit shown by
the burning candle.



WORD SHAPES (click on hay cart)

Pictures and words of objects are displayed.  This helps extend the child's
vocabulary.

Click on the picture of the object that matches the word that is shown in the
green box.



FIND THE MISSING ANIMALS (click on lilly pad)

A picture of animals is shown and some will disappear.  Uses observation, logic
and judgement to develop reading skills.

Watch the picture and remember which animals disappear.  Click on the word or
picture of the animals that have disappeared.  CLick on the thumbs-up icon and
ADI Junior will check the animals.



THE HAPPY AND SAD GAME (click on pig)

Pictures or sentences are shown and a decision has to be made as to whether it
is a happy or sad picture.  Children use observation and judgement to develop
reading with understanding.

Click on the laughing robot if the picture or sentence is happy or click on the
crying robot if not.



ANIMAL NAMES (click on cartwheel)

Pictures of animals are shown along with the name of one of the animals.
Teaches children essential reading and spelling skills.

Click on the animal that is named.



SPOT THE MISTAKE (click on well)

Pictures, words and sentences are used to help the child find mistakes.  Uses
observation and judgement.

Look at the pictures and words or the sentences and click on the one that has a
mistake in it.



RECOGNISING SOUNDS (click on windmill)

A robot holds a picture showing a word sound.  Teaches children to recognise
common letter groups.  Develops reading and spelling.

Click on the robot if the top picture has a similar sound to the picture it is
holding.  If not, click on the rubbish bin.


